  "suggestion": "[neuroscience+psychoneuroimmunology+clinical-psychology+dynamical-systems] IMPLEMENT NOW — Allostatic Load Scaling (McEwen 1998). The model already uses person.history[] and arousal but treats each situation as isolated. Allostatic load = accumulated stress burden from repeated threat exposure. Implement as: load = clamp(history.filter(threatWords).length / 5, 0, 1). Then scale: (a) need precision for safety multiplied by (1 + 2*load), (b) attractor basin depths for avoidance/rumination deepened by (1 + load), (c) autonomicState threshold lowered proportional to load so MOBILIZED triggers at lower arousal. This unifies why PTSD, burnout, and chronic anxiety produce hair-trigger threat responses and why trauma history changes baselines. One formula, three downstream effects. person.history already exists — no new fields needed. — Math: load = Σ(threatKeywords ∩ history) / historyCapacity; precisionSafety *= (1 + 2·load); basinDepth_avoidance *= (1 + load); mobilizedThreshold = 0.4 - 0.2·load; [control-theory+cognitive-psychology+motivation+self-regulation] Goal Hierarchy Interrupt (Carver & Scheier 1982). The model predicts responses from needs but doesn't respect goal-level structure. Control theory organizes goals into 3 tiers: be-goals (identity: belonging, autonomy) → do-goals (programs: achievement, fairness) → act-goals (motor: specific behaviors). When a tier-1 be-goal is threatened, it interrupts tier-2 processing — explaining why existential threats override pragmatic plans, and why belonging loss stops achievement motivation cold. Implement: infer goalTier from which needs are active; if tier-1 need has highest free-energy, force response to identity-restoration behaviors (seek connection, assert autonomy) regardless of tier-2 signals. This explains goal-interference, learned helplessness, and value-behavior alignment failures. — Math: tier(need) ∈ {1: safety/belonging/autonomy, 2: achievement/fairness/esteem, 3: understanding/pleasure}; if max(F_tier1) > θ_interrupt, suppress tier-2 responses and route to identity-repair behavior; [social-psychology+intergroup-relations+self-categorization-theory+social-cognition] Social Identity Mode Switch (Tajfel & Turner 1979). Currently the model always responds as an individual. But in group contexts, self-categorization theory predicts behavior shifts from personal identity (what do I want?) to social identity (what does my in-group expect?). Implement as a binary gate: if socialSetting contains {group, public, audience, crowd, team, peers} AND stimulus is social, activate 'group mode' — replace individual trait priors with group-typical priors (belonging precision +2×, conformity attractor depth +1.5), suppress autonomy and individual pleasure needs. This explains conformity, groupthink, deindividuation, and why the same person behaves differently alone vs. in public. Low-cost gate on existing social domain. — Math: groupMode = socialSetting ∩ {group,public,...} ≠ ∅ ∧ stimulusType=social; if groupMode: precision_belonging *= 2, depth_conform *= 1.5, precision_autonomy *= 0.4",
